Understanding Hotel Booking Behavior: A Data-Driven Analysis

2025-04-15

Introduction

Hotel reservation trends can say a lot about what people travel like, what hotels they like, and when they will most likely cancel their reservations. For hotels, this type of information is very valuable to them — it allows them to plan more efficiently, prevent last-minute cancellations, and make better business choices.

In this project, I worked with hotel reservation data in order to make sense of particular questions regarding the behavior of the customers, and identify patterns of bookings and cancellations. The objective is to determine the factors that influence bookings and what hotels can be done to enhance their services and planning.

Background

The data for this project is based on the Hotel Booking Demand dataset on Kaggle. It is actual booking information from two different types of hotels - a resort hotel and a city hotel. The data has information such as how long people stayed, when they made a reservation, whether they canceled or not, special requests, and so on.

This kind of analysis is useful because hotels can use the insights to reduce cancellations, improve customer experience, and manage their resources better. Many businesses today use data to guide their decisions, and the hotel industry is no exception. With this project, I’ve tried to understand what the data tells us about how and why people book or cancel hotel stays.

Dataset Overview

The dataset contains 119,390 hotel booking records from 2015 to 2017, mostly from Portugal. It covers both city and resort hotels, with 32 variables including booking details, guest info, and cancellation status.

About 37% of bookings were canceled, making the is_canceled variable important. Time-related columns like arrival_date_year, arrival_date_month, and lead_time(difference between booking and arrival date in days) show guests booked up to 737 days in advance.

Categorical variables include hotel type, meal plan, market segment, and country. The agent and company columns had too many “NULL” values and were not used in analysis.

Some entries had outliers or errors—like bookings with 55 adults or negative room rates. The children column also had a few missing values. These issues guided the cleaning and transformation of the data for accurate analysis.

Methodology

To explore the hotel booking data and answer five key questions, I used R for data handling, visualization, and analysis. The project was done in RStudio and compiled using RMarkdown, which allows both the code and output to be displayed together.

For each question, I started by making an assumption — like what I thought would happen — then explored the data using code and charts in R. Finally, I compared my assumption with what the data actually showed.

Initial Data Cleaning

  1. Drop Unnecessary Columns: I removed the reservation_status_date, agent, and company columns because they do not provide useful insights for the analysis and are redundant.

- reservation_status_date is too specific

- agent and company columns have a lot of NA values.

# Dropping 'reservation_status_date', 'agent', and 'company' columns
# These columns are not contributing meaningfully to the analysis, 
# and 'agent' and 'company' are too granular/redundant.

hotel_data <- hotel_data %>%
  select(-reservation_status_date, -agent, -company)
  1. Create a Single Date Column for Arrival Date - I combined the arrival year, month, and day to create a single arrival_date column. This allows easier sorting of dates later on.
# Creating a single 'arrival_date' column by combining year, month (converted to number), 
# and day of the month for easier sorting and analysis.
hotel_data <- hotel_data %>%
  mutate(arrival_date = as.Date(paste(arrival_date_year,
                                      match(arrival_date_month, month.name),
                                      arrival_date_day_of_month, sep = "-")))
  1. Drop Old Date Variables- Since I’ve now created the arrival_date column, I removed the old date columns that are no longer needed.
# Dropping the old date components (year, month, day, week number) as we now have a single 'arrival_date' column
hotel_data <- hotel_data %>%
  select(-arrival_date_year, -arrival_date_month, -arrival_date_day_of_month, -arrival_date_week_number)
  1. Group Countries with < 50 Bookings as “Other” - I created a group of countries that have fewer than 50 bookings and assigned them to the “Other” category. I excluded “NULL” values from being grouped as “Other”.
# Group countries with fewer than 50 bookings as "Other"
# Excluding 'NULL' from this group and leaving NA values untouched
country_counts <- hotel_data %>% count(country, sort = TRUE)
rare_countries <- (country_counts %>% filter(n < 50 & country != "NULL"))$country  # Exclude "NULL"

hotel_data <- hotel_data %>% 
  mutate(country = if_else(country %in% rare_countries, "Other", country))
  1. Create Total Stay Duration (Weekend + Week Nights) - I combined the weekend nights and week nights columns into one stay_duration column to represent the total stay length.
# Creating a new 'stay_duration' column by adding weekend nights and week nights
hotel_data <- hotel_data %>%
  mutate(stay_duration = stays_in_weekend_nights + stays_in_week_nights)
  1. Create Total Number of Guests (Adults + Children + Babies) - I created a total_guests column that sums up the number of adults, children, and babies for each booking, providing a better overall view of the guest count.
# Calculate revenue only for non-canceled bookings (adr * stay duration)
# If booking is canceled, revenue is set to 0
hotel_data <- hotel_data %>%
  mutate(revenue = if_else(is_canceled == 0, adr * stay_duration, 0))
  1. Calculate Revenue for Non-Canceled Bookings - I created a revenue column that multiplies ADR (average daily rate) by the stay duration for non-canceled bookings. If the booking is canceled (is_cancelled == 1), the revenue is set to 0.
# Calculate revenue only for non-canceled bookings (adr * stay duration)
# If booking is canceled, revenue is set to 0
hotel_data <- hotel_data %>%
  mutate(revenue = if_else(is_canceled == 0, adr * stay_duration, 0))
  1. Replace Meal Codes with Descriptive Labels - I replaced the meal codes (BB, FB, etc.) with full descriptive labels like “Breakfast Only” and “Full Board” for better readability.
# Replacing meal codes with clearer, more readable labels
hotel_data <- hotel_data %>%
  mutate(meal = recode(meal,
                       "BB" = "Breakfast Only",
                       "FB" = "Full Board",
                       "HB" = "Half Board",
                       "SC" = "No Meal",
                       "Undefined" = "Not Specified"))
  1. Replace Customer Type Codes with Clearer Labels - I replaced the customer type codes (Transient, Group, etc.) with more descriptive labels like “Walk-in”, “Corporate”, and “Organized Group” for easier interpretation.
# Replacing customer type codes with clearer labels
hotel_data <- hotel_data %>%
  mutate(customer_type = recode(customer_type,
                                "Transient" = "Walk-in",
                                "Transient-Party" = "Group Walk-in",
                                "Contract" = "Corporate",
                                "Group" = "Organized Group"))

Questions

  1. How do special requests and assigned room types influence guest satisfaction and stay duration?
  2. How do lead time and booking cancellations impact revenue?
  3. How does the country of origin influence booking behavior and lead time?
  4. Does the presence of meal packages affect booking modifications or cancellations?
  5. How do waiting list bookings and repeated guest status affect stay modifications and cancellations?

Q1. How do special requests and assigned room types influence guest satisfaction and stay duration?

Variables Used:

  • total_of_special_requests

  • reserved_room_type

  • assigned_room_type

  • stay_duration (already created)

  • is_canceled

Step 1: Create a column to check if room types match

hotel_data <- hotel_data %>%
  mutate(room_match = if_else(reserved_room_type == assigned_room_type, "Matched", "Mismatched"))

Step 2: Lineplot – Stay duration by number of special requests

Assumption: More special requests suggest greater guest investment, likely leading to longer stays.

# Avg stay duration for each number of special requests
stay_by_requests <- hotel_data %>%
  group_by(total_of_special_requests) %>%
  summarise(avg_stay = mean(stay_duration))

# View numeric output
print(stay_by_requests)
## # A tibble: 6 × 2
##   total_of_special_requests avg_stay
##                       <int>    <dbl>
## 1                         0     3.27
## 2                         1     3.59
## 3                         2     3.75
## 4                         3     3.98
## 5                         4     4.32
## 6                         5     4.65
# Plot: Line plot
ggplot(stay_by_requests, aes(x = total_of_special_requests, y = avg_stay)) +
  geom_line(color = "darkgreen", size = 1) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  labs(title = "Average Stay Duration by Special Requests",
       x = "Number of Special Requests",
       y = "Average Stay Duration (nights)")

Result: Stay duration increases from 3.27 nights (0 requests) to 4.65 nights (5 requests).

Conclusion: Assumption matched. More requests often indicate planned, meaningful stays.

Step 3: Barchart – Stay duration by room match/mismatch

Assumption: Matched rooms lead to better guest experience and longer stays.

# Avg stay duration based on room match
stay_by_room <- hotel_data %>%
  group_by(room_match) %>%
  summarise(avg_stay = mean(stay_duration))

# View numeric output
print(stay_by_room)
## # A tibble: 2 × 2
##   room_match avg_stay
##   <chr>         <dbl>
## 1 Matched        3.52
## 2 Mismatched     2.77
# Plot: Bar chart
ggplot(stay_by_room, aes(x = room_match, y = avg_stay, fill = room_match)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  geom_text(aes(label = round(avg_stay, 2)), vjust = -0.5) +
  labs(title = "Average Stay Duration: Matched by Mismatched Rooms",
       x = "Room Assignment Match",
       y = "Average Stay Duration (nights)")

Result: Matched rooms = 3.52 nights; Mismatched = 2.77 nights.

Conclusion: Assumption matched. Receiving the booked room improves guest trust and experience.

Step 4: Cancellation rate by special requests

Assumption: Guests with more requests are less likely to cancel.

# Calculate cancellation rate for each special request count
cancellation_by_requests <- hotel_data %>%
  group_by(total_of_special_requests) %>%
  summarise(cancel_rate = mean(is_canceled))

# View numeric output
print(cancellation_by_requests)

Step 5: Does Room Matching Affect Cancellation Rates?

Assumption: Mismatched rooms lead to higher cancellations.

# Numeric output
hotel_data %>%
  group_by(room_match) %>%
  summarise(cancellation_rate = mean(is_canceled))
## # A tibble: 2 × 2
##   room_match cancellation_rate
##   <chr>                  <dbl>
## 1 Matched               0.416 
## 2 Mismatched            0.0538
# Bar chart (still helpful here)
ggplot(hotel_data %>%
         group_by(room_match) %>%
         summarise(cancellation_rate = mean(is_canceled)),
       aes(x = room_match, y = cancellation_rate, fill = room_match)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(title = "Cancellation Rate by Room Match",
       x = "Room Assignment",
       y = "Cancellation Rate")

Result: Matched = 41.6%, Mismatched = 5.3%.

Conclusion: This is misleading—room match is known only after check-in. Mismatched rooms can’t exist for canceled bookings.

Q2. How does lead time and booking cancellations impact revenue?

Variables used:

  • lead_time

  • is_canceled

  • adr (Average Daily Rate)

  • stay_duration (already created)

  • revenue = adr * stay_duration

Step 1: Bar Chart – Average Revenue by Cancellation Status

Assumption: Canceled bookings bring in ₹0 revenue, while non-canceled bookings generate revenue.

# Average revenue by cancellation status
avg_revenue <- hotel_data %>%
  filter(!is.na(revenue)) %>%
  group_by(is_canceled) %>%
  summarise(avg_rev = mean(revenue, na.rm = TRUE))

avg_revenue

Results

Q1: Special Requests & Room Match Impact

  • Stay duration increases with more special requests (from 3.27 to 4.65 nights).

  • Guests with matched rooms stay longer (3.52 nights) than those with mismatched rooms (2.77 nights).

  • Cancellation rate drops sharply as special requests increase — from 47.7% to just 5%.

  • Room mismatch does not increase cancellations (matched: 41.6%, mismatched: only 5.3%).

Q2: Revenue, Lead Time & Cancellation

  • Canceled bookings generate ₹0, while completed bookings average ₹346 in revenue.

  • Cancellation rate rises with lead time — from ~21% (0–25 days) to over 80% (>400 days).

  • Revenue peaks at 150–200 lead days (₹490–500) and drops significantly after 375 days (₹245), with no clear explanation.

Q3: Country-Based Behavior

  • Lead times highest for Germany, UK, and Ireland (~120–137 days); shortest for Spain and Netherlands (~55–80 days).

  • Portugal has the highest cancellation rate (~56.6%); Germany, Netherlands, France have low rates (~16–18%).

  • Special requests highest from Belgium (87.5%) and Brazil (82.3%); lowest from Portugal (36.7%).

  • Most booking changes from Netherlands (0.289) and UK (0.283); least from Portugal (0.170).

Q4: Meal Type Insights

  • Full Board guests cancel most (59.9%); “Not Specified” cancel least (24.5%).

  • Most booking changes come from “Not Specified” meal types (0.369); least from “No Meal” (0.172).

  • “Breakfast Only” is the most popular meal plan (92,310 bookings); “Full Board” the least popular (798 bookings).

Q5: Guest Type & Waitlist Behavior

  • Repeated guests cancel less (14.5%) than new guests (37.8%).

  • Repeated guests make more changes (0.265 vs 0.220).

  • Waitlisted guests cancel more (63.8% vs 36.2%).

  • Waitlisted guests make fewer changes (0.159 vs 0.223).

Conclusion

Q1:

  • Guests who make more special requests usually stay longer and are much less likely to cancel their bookings, which shows they are more committed and satisfied.

  • Also, people who get the same room type they booked tend to stay a bit longer, likely because they feel their expectations were met.

  • However, the data on room mismatches and cancellations is tricky—since cancellations happen before rooms are assigned, we can’t say mismatched rooms cause fewer cancellations.

  • Overall, special requests are a strong sign of guest satisfaction, and giving people what they ask for can lead to better experiences and fewer cancellations.

Q2:

  • Guest behavior around cancellations is strongly influenced by how early they book — longer lead times are linked with much higher cancellation rates.

  • Canceled bookings bring in no revenue, while non-canceled ones contribute significantly.

  • Interestingly, revenue doesn’t always drop with longer lead times, though one specific drop couldn’t be fully explained, marking a limitation.

  • These insights can help hotels tailor strategies to reduce cancellations and maximize revenue.

Q3:

  • Overall, country-wise analysis reveals that international guests — especially from countries like Germany, the UK, and the Netherlands — tend to book earlier, make more changes to their bookings, and request more customized services.

  • This shows their trips are more planned and purposeful. In contrast, local guests from Portugal often book closer to the stay date, cancel more frequently, and make fewer requests or changes, suggesting more casual or spontaneous travel behavior.

  • These patterns reflect how geography and travel complexity influence guest behavior and expectations.

Q4:

Overall, meal type plays an interesting role in guest behavior.

  • Guests with “Not Specified” or structured meal plans tend to make more booking changes, possibly because they book earlier or as part of tour packages.

  • However, contrary to expectations, Full Board bookings had the highest cancellation rate, suggesting that these high-commitment bookings may also carry more uncertainty.

  • In terms of popularity, “Breakfast Only” dominates, likely due to its affordability and flexibility, while Full Board remains a niche choice.

  • These insights can help hotels design meal plans and policies that match guest preferences and booking patterns.

Q5:

  • Waitlisted guests show distinct behavior — they cancel much more frequently (63.8% vs 36.2%) and make fewer booking changes (0.159 vs 0.223). This suggests that uncertainty in reservation confirmation leads them to either cancel outright or avoid modifying bookings.

  • In contrast, non-waitlisted guests are more stable in their plans, showing lower cancellation rates and a higher willingness to update their bookings.

  • Addressing waitlist uncertainty quickly could help reduce cancellations and improve engagement.

Appendix

A. Variable names and meaning in the dataset:

hotel – Type of hotel (e.g., Resort Hotel or City Hotel)

is_canceled – 1 if the booking was canceled, 0 if not

lead_time – Number of days between the booking date and the arrival date

arrival_date_year – Year of arrival

arrival_date_month – Month of arrival

arrival_date_week_number – Week number of the arrival date

arrival_date_day_of_month – Day of the month for arrival

stays_in_weekend_nights – Number of weekend nights (Saturday or Sunday)

stays_in_week_nights – Number of weekday nights (Monday–Friday)

adults – Number of adults

children – Number of children

babies – Number of babies

meal – Type of meal (BB, HB, FB)

country – Country of origin of the guest

market_segment – Market segment that made the booking (Direct, Corporate, Online TA, etc.)

distribution_channel – Distribution channel (Direct, TA/TO, etc.)

is_repeated_guest – 1 if a repeated guest, 0 otherwise

previous_cancellations – Number of previous cancellations

previous_bookings_not_canceled – Number of previous bookings that were not canceled

reserved_room_type – Code of the reserved room type

assigned_room_type – Code of the assigned room type

booking_changes – Number of changes made to the booking

deposit_type – Type of deposit (No Deposit, Non Refund, etc.)

agent – ID of the travel agent that made the booking

company – ID of the company that made the booking

days_in_waiting_list – Number of days the booking was on the waiting list

customer_type – Type of customer (Transient, Group, etc.)

adr – Average Daily Rate (ADR), i.e., revenue per available room

required_car_parking_spaces – Number of required parking spaces

total_of_special_requests – Number of special requests made by the guest

reservation_status – Status of the reservation (Check-Out, Canceled, etc.)

reservation_status_date – Date when the last status was updated

GBR -> United Kingdom
